data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14 / .NET 10, **new built-in span conversions** cause `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (a span-based method) instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. Span-based methods **cannot be represented in expression trees**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by disambiguating:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three ensure the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains` overload is selected, which is representable in expression trees.
